[INFO:swift] [LABELS] [-100 * 467]The image consists of CT and MR scans for a patient who has an implanted fiducial and underwent irradiation for residual disease after prostatectomy. The scans help to distinguish the fiducial from surgical clips.<|im_end|>
[-100 * 469]The image includes both CT (Computed Tomography) and MR (Magnetic Resonance) imaging modalities.<|im_end|>
[-100 * 470]What stands out in this image are the implanted markers, which appear as a very large dark signal on 3D bFFE, mDixon water, and T2-weighted MRI sequences.<|im_end|>
[-100 * 470]Yes, there are multiple sub-figures in this image, each showing different imaging sequences and modalities.<|im_end|>
[-100 * 471]Sub-figure (a) shows a CT scan of the patient with the implanted fiducial. The fiducial and surgical clips are visible, and the image helps in distinguishing between the two.<|im_end|>
[-100 * 472]Sub-figure (b) displays a 3D bFFE MR image of the patient. In this image, the implanted markers are seen as a very large dark signal, which helps in identifying their location.<|im_end|>
[-100 * 472]Sub-figure (c) presents an mDixon water MR image of the patient. Similar to the 3D bFFE image, the implanted markers appear as a large dark signal, making it easier to differentiate them from the surgical clips.<|im_end|>
[-100 * 470]Sub-figure (d) shows a T2-weighted MRI sequence of the patient. As in the other MR images, the implanted markers are visible as a prominent dark signal, which aids in distinguishing them from the surrounding surgical clips.<|im_end|>

